    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic metabolism, which occurs when muscles don't receive enough oxygen to generate energy from glucose. During intense, high-energy activities like HIIT, muscles rely on iron-rich molecules (myoglobin) to store oxygen, but when muscles exhaust their oxygen supply, they switch to anaerobic glycolysis, producing energy-rich molecules and lactic acid as a waste product. As lactic acid builds up, it causes muscle fatigue and soreness. Thankfully, after a set, your body can eliminate lactic acid through increased blood flow, breathing, and other mechanisms that help deliver to and remove creatine kinase, an enzyme that breaks down lactic acid for energy. This process is often facilitated by post-workout stretching and cardio.",
