    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. so basically it's just like a buildup of metabolic waste because of the lack of oxygen, right? but does that buildup actually cause the physical feeling of pain or burning during the set, or is that something else happening in the muscle tissue at the same time?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The physical feeling of pain or burning is thought to be due to several mechanisms, and lactic acid buildup may contribute to some of it. The production of lactic acid causes muscle contractions to become slightly less efficient and can lead to a decrease in muscle force production. Some research suggests that lactic acid may also stimulate the pain-sensing nerve endings in the muscle tissue, contributing to the burning sensation. Additionally, the acidification of the muscle environment can lead to the activation of other pain-producing pathways, such as the release of prostaglandins and other neurotransmitters. So, while lactic acid buildup is a key contributor, it's not the sole cause of the physical feeling of pain or burning.",
